      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, my tomato plants are acting weird. the leaves on the bottom of the stems are turning this sickly yellow color but the top ones look okay. what's probably going on and how do i fix the soil?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, it sounds like your tomato plants are suffering from a condition known as \"lower stem chlorosis.\" This is often caused by a lack of iron in the soil, which is essential for the plants to produce chlorophyll and carry out photosynthesis. To fix the soil, you might consider adding some iron chelates or Epsom salts to the soil, which can help the plants absorb the iron more effectively. Just remember, if you're dealing with a soil that's too acidic, you might need to adjust the pH level first. And always be cautious when adding any new substances to your garden, as too much of anything can be as harmful as too little. Keep an eye on your plants, and if they start looking more like a healthy tomato plant, you'll know you've done the trick. Happy gardening, and may your tomatoes be as bountiful as a treasure hoard of goblins!",
